<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is CORS?", answer: "Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) is a security mechanism that allows a web page from one origin (domain, scheme, port) to request resources from a different origin. Without CORS, browsers enforce the same-origin policy, which blocks cross-origin requests by default. CORS headers in the server response tell the browser which cross-origin requests are permitted." },
  { question: "What is a preflight request?", answer: "A preflight request is an HTTP OPTIONS request that the browser sends automatically before certain cross-origin requests. It occurs when the request uses methods other than GET, HEAD, or POST, or includes custom headers, or uses a Content-Type other than application/x-www-form-urlencoded, multipart/form-data, or text/plain. The server responds with CORS headers indicating whether the actual request is allowed." },
  { question: "Why is wildcard origin with credentials dangerous?", answer: "When Access-Control-Allow-Origin is set to * (wildcard) and Access-Control-Allow-Credentials is true, browsers will reject the request entirely. This combination is not allowed because credentials (cookies, HTTP authentication) are sensitive, and allowing any origin to send credentialed requests would be a major security vulnerability. Instead, the server must echo the specific requesting origin." },
  { question: "What is the Vary: Origin header and why does it matter?", answer: "When a server returns a specific origin in Access-Control-Allow-Origin (not a wildcard), it should also include Vary: Origin in the response. This tells caches that the response varies based on the Origin request header. Without it, a cache might serve a response intended for origin A to origin B, which would be blocked by the browser, causing intermittent CORS failures." },
  { question: "How do I fix CORS errors?", answer: "CORS errors are fixed on the server, not the client. Add the appropriate Access-Control-Allow-Origin header (specific origin or *), Access-Control-Allow-Methods for non-simple methods, and Access-Control-Allow-Headers for custom headers. For credentialed requests, set Access-Control-Allow-Credentials to true and use a specific origin (not *). Ensure preflight responses include these headers and return a 2xx status code." }
]) %>

